04885nam a22005535i 9780822383406DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223834067 a10.1515/97808223834062doi  a(DE-B1597)551887  a(OCoLC)1055302143  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE184.A1bB899 2002 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a322.4/4/0973090451 aBurlein, Ann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLift High the Cross :bWhere White Supremacy and the Christian Right Converge /cAnn Burlein. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (303 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tThe Violence of Culture: Countermemory and Niche Marketed Masculinity -- t1 Countermemory, Children, and Ignorance-Power -- t2 Converging Case Studies -- tChristian Identity, Scriptures for America, and Pete Peters -- t3 Mainstream Roots -- t4 Biblical Memories and the Erotics of Domination -- t5 Nichemarketing the Apocalypse -- tThe Christian Right, Focus on the Family, and James Dobson -- t6 The Power of Soft-Sell Style -- t7 Remembering the Sixties as Pop Cultural Conspiracy -- t8 Nichemarketing the Family Homestead -- tConclusion -- t9 The Bowl, the Crossing Point, and the Moment After -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography of Secondary Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBoth the Christian right and right-wing white supremacist groups aspire to overcome a culture they perceive as hostile to the white middle class, families, and heterosexuality. The family is threatened, they claim, by a secular humanist conspiracy that seeks to erase all memory of the nation’s Christian heritage by brainwashing its children through sex education, multiculturalism, and pop culture. In Lift High the Cross Ann Burlein looks at two groups that represent, in one case, the “hard” right, and in the other, the “soft” right—Pete Peters’s “Scriptures for America” and James Dobson’s “Focus on the Family”—in order to investigate the specific methods these groups rely on to appeal to their followers.Arguing that today’s right engenders its popularity not by overt bigotry or hatred but by focusing on people’s hopes for their children, Burlein finds a politics of grief at the heart of such rhetoric. While demonstrating how religious symbols, rituals, texts, and practices shape people’s memories and their investment in society, she shows how Peters and Dobson each construct countermemories for their followers that reframe their histories and identities—as well as their worlds—by reversing mainstream perspectives in ways that counter existing power relations. By employing the techniques of niche marketing, the politics of scandal, and the transformation of political issues into “gut issues” and by remasculinizing the body politic, Burlein shows, such groups are able to move people into their realm of influence without requiring them to agree with all their philosophical, doctrinal, or political positions.Lift High the Cross will appeal to students and scholars of religion, American cultural studies, women’s studies, sociology, and gay and lesbian studies, as well as to non-specialists interested in American politics and, specifically, the right.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChristianity and politicszUnited States. 0aRight-wing extremistszUnited States. 0aWhite supremacy movementszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822383406zCo-access DOI >> click Walt